# CLAUDE.md

This file provides guidance to Claude Code (claude.ai/code) when working with code in this repository.

## Project Overview

This is a **modular keyboard framework** designed for multi-mode wireless keyboards and touchpads. It provides a cross-platform, layered architecture supporting multiple MCU platforms (PixArt 2860, WCH CH584, Nordic nRF52 series). The framework is inspired by QMK firmware's key processing pipeline and implements a clean separation of concerns through HAL (Hardware Abstraction Layer), driver, middleware, and application layers.

## Repository Structure

```
keyboard-framework/
├── hal/                        # Hardware Abstraction Layer
│   ├── interface/              # HAL interfaces (GPIO, ADC, PWM, I2C, UART, Timer, Power)
│   └── platforms/              # Platform-specific HAL implementations
├── drivers/                    # Device Drivers
│   ├── communication/          # BLE, USB, 2.4G wireless protocols
│   ├── input/                  # Keyboard matrix, touchpad, buttons
│   ├── output/                 # LEDs, backlight, indicators
│   ├── storage/                # EEPROM, Flash storage
│   ├── power/                  # Battery monitoring, power management
│   └── system/                 # Timers, watchdog, event management
├── middleware/                 # Middleware Services
│   ├── config/                 # Configuration management
│   ├── protocol/               # HID protocol processing
│   └── keyboard/               # Key mapping, combo handling
├── keyboards/                  # Product-specific configurations
│   └── keymaps/                # Key layout definitions
├── application/                # Application layer
│   └── main.c                  # Main application entry
├── utils/                      # Utilities (ring buffer, CRC, logger)
└── test/                       # Test utilities and Unity framework
```

## Build System

### Configuration
- **CMake**: Minimum version 3.29
- **C Standard**: GNU C11
- **Build Generators**: Visual Studio 17 2022 or Ninja
- **Target Platform**: ARM MCUs (cross-compiled)

### Build Commands

#### For MCU Development (ARM Cross-Compiler)

```bash
# ARM GCC (arm-none-eabi-gcc) must be installed
# Configure and build with Ninja
cd D:/Code/C_Project/keyboard-framework
mkdir cmake-build-debug && cd cmake-build-debug

# Configure with ARM cross-compiler
cmake -G Ninja -DCMAKE_C_COMPILER=arm-none-eabi-gcc -DCMAKE_SYSTEM_NAME=Generic -DCMAKE_SYSTEM_PROCESSOR=arm -DCMAKE_TRY_COMPILE_TARGET_TYPE=STATIC_LIBRARY ..

# Build the project
ninja

# Clean rebuild
cd ..
rm -rf cmake-build-debug
mkdir cmake-build-debug && cd cmake-build-debug
cmake -G Ninja -DCMAKE_C_COMPILER=arm-none-eabi-gcc -DCMAKE_SYSTEM_NAME=Generic -DCMAKE_SYSTEM_PROCESSOR=arm -DCMAKE_TRY_COMPILE_TARGET_TYPE=STATIC_LIBRARY ..
ninja
```

#### With Environment Variable (Alternative)

```bash
cd D:/Code/C_Project/keyboard-framework
set CC=arm-none-eabi-gcc
mkdir cmake-build-debug && cd cmake-build-debug
cmake -G Ninja -DCMAKE_TRY_COMPILE_TARGET_TYPE=STATIC_LIBRARY ..
ninja
```

#### For CLion IDE

CLion automatically detects CMake and uses the configured compiler. Ensure `CMAKE_C_COMPILER` is set to `arm-none-eabi-gcc` in CMakeLists.txt before importing.

### CMake Configuration Key Points

- Source files are manually listed in CMakeLists.txt (not auto-discovered)
- The main executable is built from `main.c`
- ARM embedded linker flags: `-nostartfiles -lgcc -lc -lnosys`
- Include paths configured for all major directories
- Currently builds only core modules: matrix, debounce, timer, action, layer
